Filter Expression Gotchas

1. Filters do NOT short-circuit

In a single run like `[<var>is[blank]then[yes]else{!!field}enlist-input<var>]`, ALL operators execute sequentially. `then[yes]` does NOT stop the chain — `enlist-input` still runs and can wipe out the result.

```
<!-- BROKEN — enlist-input runs even after then[yes] -->
[<var>is[blank]then[yes]else{!!field}enlist-input<var>match<x>]

<!-- CORRECT — use ~ (else) between separate runs -->
[<var>is[blank]then[yes]] ~[{!!field}enlist-input[]match<var>then[yes]]
```

The `~` operator means "use next run only if previous returned empty".

---

2. `:filter` does not support `!` negation

Negated operators like `!has[field]` and `!is[blank]` silently fail inside `:filter` — they produce no output, filtering out every item.

```
<!-- BROKEN — !has silently returns nothing, all items filtered out -->
[tag[X]]:filter[<currentTiddler>!has[my-field]]

<!-- CORRECT — chain !has directly in the run -->
[tag[X]!has[my-field]]

<!-- CORRECT — if you must use :filter, invert the logic -->
[tag[X]]:filter[<currentTiddler>get[my-field]is[blank]then[yes]]
<!-- (but this also has issues — see gotcha #3) -->
```

---

3. `get[field]` returns nothing (not "") for missing/empty fields

`get[fieldname]` on a missing or empty field returns **no output** — not an empty string. So `is[blank]` after `get` on a missing field has no input and produces nothing.

```
<!-- BROKEN — get returns nothing, is[blank] has no input -->
:filter[<currentTiddler>get[my-field]is[blank]]

<!-- CORRECT — use !has for missing/empty fields -->
[<tiddlers>!has[my-field]]
```

`has[field]` returns true only when the field exists AND is non-empty.

---

4. Variable names with dots don't work in `<>` syntax

`<f.status>` in a filter does NOT resolve a variable named `f.status`. The dot breaks variable resolution.

```
<!-- BROKEN -->
<$let f.status="active">[<f.status>match[active]]</$let>

<!-- CORRECT — use camelCase or hyphens -->
<$let fStatus="active">[<fStatus>match[active]]</$let>
```

---

5. `\function` body is single-line only

Everything after `\function name(params)` on the SAME line is the filter. Continuation lines become visible body text.

```
<!-- BROKEN — line 2 is body text, not part of the function -->
\function myFunc()
  [all[tiddlers]tag[X]]

<!-- CORRECT — entire filter on one line -->
\function myFunc() [all[tiddlers]tag[X]] :filter[get[status]match[active]]
```

---

6. Operator chaining after `function[]` — watch the brackets

After `function[name]`, the `]]` looks like a closing run. Chaining operators AFTER `]]` puts them outside the run.

```
<!-- BROKEN — count[] is outside the run -->
[function[myFunc]]count[]

<!-- CORRECT — chain inside the same run -->
[function[myFunc]count[]]

<!-- CORRECT — new run with + prefix -->
[function[myFunc]] +[count[]]
```

---

7. `<now>` vs `now[]` vs `<<now>>`

- `<now>` in a filter — NOT a standard variable, produces wrong results
- `<<now "DDth MMM YYYY">>` — standard TW macro for display
- For filter comparison: capture into a variable first with `$let`

```
<!-- Display -->
<<now "DDth MMM YYYY">>

<!-- Filter comparison -->
<$let today={{{[<now YYYY0MM0DD>]}}}>
  [<today>compare:date:gt[20260101]]
</$let>
```

---

8. `[[` and `]]` cannot be used as literal strings in filters

Double square brackets are filter syntax delimiters (title literals). You cannot produce them via `addprefix` or `addsuffix` inside a filter — they get interpreted as filter syntax, not as literal characters.

```
<!-- BROKEN — [[ and ]] are parsed as filter delimiters -->
[<title>addprefix[[[]addsuffix[]]]]

<!-- CORRECT — store brackets in variables, then reference them -->
<$let ob="[[" cb="]]"
  wrapped={{{ [<title>addprefix<ob>addsuffix<cb>] }}}>
  <!-- wrapped = "[[My Tiddler]]" as a literal string -->
</$let>
```

This commonly comes up when building filter expressions as strings (e.g., for `allowFilter` or dynamic `$list` filters) where tiddler titles need `[[bracket]]` wrapping to handle spaces.

---

9. `subfilter` with literal filter operands — nested brackets break parsing

`[subfilter[tag[sensitive]]]` does NOT work. The parser sees `[subfilter[tag[sensitive]` as the operand and `]]` as the closing brackets, producing a malformed filter.

```
<!-- BROKEN — nested brackets confuse the parser -->
[subfilter[tag[sensitive]]]

<!-- CORRECT — use {tiddler-reference} to read the filter from a tiddler's text field -->
[subfilter{$:/config/my-protection-filter}]

<!-- CORRECT — use <variable> if filter is in a variable -->
<$let myFilter="[tag[sensitive]]">
  [subfilter<myFilter>]
</$let>
```

This applies to any operator that takes a filter expression as its operand (`subfilter`, `filter`, `reduce`, `map`, etc.). Always use indirection via `{tiddler}` or `<variable>` — never embed a filter literally inside `[]` brackets.

---

10. `jsonget` chain fails on array items — use `jsonextract` first

When iterating a JSON array with `:map`, chaining `jsonget<currentTiddler>jsonget[field]` silently returns empty. The second `jsonget` doesn't receive the sub-object. Use `jsonextract` to extract the sub-object, then `jsonget` on the result:

```
<!-- BROKEN — jsonget<idx>jsonget[id] returns empty for every item -->
[<cache>get[text]jsonindexes[]] :map[<cache>get[text]jsonget<currentTiddler>jsonget[id]]

<!-- CORRECT — jsonextract gets the sub-object, then jsonget reads the field -->
[<cache>get[text]jsonindexes[]] :map:flat[<cache>get[text]jsonextract<currentTiddler>jsonget[id]]
```

Note the `:flat` suffix on `:map` — required when the mapped expression returns a single value per item.
